# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: adjacency-matrix-viz
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] In graph theory and computer science, an **adjacency matrix** is a square matrix used to represent a finite graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] The elements of the matrix indicate whether pairs of vertices are adjacent or not within the graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] In the special case of a finite simple graph, the adjacency matrix is a (0,1)-matrix with zeros on its diagonal.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] If the graph is undirected (i.e. all of its edges are bidirectional), the adjacency matrix is symmetric.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] The relationship between a graph and the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of its adjacency matrix is studied in spectral graph theory.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] The adjacency matrix of a graph should be distinguished from its incidence matrix, a different matrix representation whose elements indicate whether vertex–edge pairs are incident or not, and its degree matrix, which contains information about the degree of each vertex.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] For a simple graph with vertex set *U* = {*u*1, ..., *u**n*}, the adjacency matrix is a square *n* × *n* matrix A such that its element Aij is 1 when there is an edge from vertex *u*i to vertex *u*j, and 0 when there is no edge.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] The diagonal elements of the matrix are all 0, since edges from a vertex to itself (loops) are not allowed in simple graphs.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] It is also sometimes useful in algebraic graph theory to replace the nonzero elements with algebraic variables.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] The same concept can be extended to multigraphs and graphs with loops by storing the number of edges between each two vertices in the corresponding matrix element, and by allowing nonzero diagonal elements.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] Loops may be counted either once (as a single edge) or twice (as two vertex-edge incidences), as long as a consistent convention is followed.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] Undirected graphs often use the latter convention of counting loops twice, whereas directed graphs typically use the former convention.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] where B is an *r* × *s* matrix, and 0*r*,*r* and 0*s*,*s* represent the *r* × *r* and *s* × *s* zero matrices.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] In this case, the smaller matrix B uniquely represents the graph, and the remaining parts of A can be discarded as redundant.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] B is sometimes called the *biadjacency matrix*.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] The biadjacency matrix is the *r* × *s* 0–1 matrix B in which *b**i*,*j* = 1 if and only if (*u**i*, *v**j*) ∈ *E*.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] If G is a bipartite multigraph or weighted graph, then the elements b*i,j* are taken to be the number of edges between the vertices or the weight of the edge (*u**i*, *v**j*), respectively.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] An (*a*, *b*, *c*)-adjacency matrix A of a simple graph has *A**i*,*j* = *a* if (*i*, *j*) is an edge, b if it is not, and c on the diagonal.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] The Seidel adjacency matrix is a (−1, 1, 0)-adjacency matrix.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] This matrix is used in studying strongly regular graphs and two-graphs.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] The distance matrix has in position (*i*, *j*) the distance between vertices vi and vj.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] The distance is the length of a shortest path connecting the vertices.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] Unless lengths of edges are explicitly provided, the length of a path is the number of edges in it.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] The distance matrix resembles a high power of the adjacency matrix, but instead of telling only whether or not two vertices are connected (i.e., the connection matrix, which contains Boolean values), it gives the exact distance between them.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] The convention followed here (for undirected graphs) is that each edge adds 1 to the appropriate cell in the matrix, and each loop (an edge from a vertex to itself) adds 2 to the appropriate cell on the diagonal in the matrix.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] This allows the degree of a vertex to be easily found by taking the sum of the values in either its respective row or column in the adjacency matrix.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] The adjacency matrix of a directed graph can be asymmetric.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] The former definition is commonly used in graph theory and social network analysis (e.g., sociology, political science, economics, psychology).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] The latter is more common in other applied sciences (e.g., dynamical systems, physics, network science) where A is sometimes used to describe linear dynamics on graphs.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] Using the first definition, the in-degrees of a vertex can be computed by summing the entries of the corresponding column and the out-degree of vertex by summing the entries of the corresponding row.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] When using the second definition, the in-degree of a vertex is given by the corresponding row sum and the out-degree is given by the corresponding column sum.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] The adjacency matrix of a complete graph contains all ones except along the diagonal where there are only zeros.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] The adjacency matrix of an empty graph is a zero matrix.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] The adjacency matrix of an undirected simple graph is symmetric, and therefore has a complete set of real eigenvalues and an orthogonal eigenvector basis.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] The set of eigenvalues of a graph is the **spectrum** of the graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] The greatest eigenvalue $\lambda _{1}$ is bounded above by the maximum degree.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] This can be seen as result of the Perron–Frobenius theorem, but it can be proved easily.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] Let v be one eigenvector associated to $\lambda _{1}$ and x the entry in which v has maximum absolute value.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] Without loss of generality assume vx is positive since otherwise you simply take the eigenvector -v, also associated to $\lambda _{1}$ .
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] For d-regular graphs, d is the first eigenvalue of A for the vector *v* = (1, ..., 1) (it is easy to check that it is an eigenvalue and it is the maximum because of the above bound).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] The multiplicity of this eigenvalue is the number of connected components of G, in particular $\lambda _{1}>\lambda _{2}$ for connected graphs.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] It can be shown that for each eigenvalue $\lambda _{i}$ , its opposite $-\lambda _{i}=\lambda _{n+1-i}$ is also an eigenvalue of A if G is a bipartite graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] In particular −d is an eigenvalue of any d-regular bipartite graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] The difference $\lambda _{1}-\lambda _{2}$ is called the spectral gap and it is related to the expansion of G.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] It is also useful to introduce the spectral radius of A denoted by $\lambda (G)=\max _{\left|\lambda _{i}\right|<d}|\lambda _{i}|$ .
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] This bound is tight in the Ramanujan graphs.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] Suppose two directed or undirected graphs *G*1 and *G*2 with adjacency matrices *A*1 and *A*2 are given.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] In particular, *A*1 and *A*2 are similar and therefore have the same minimal polynomial, characteristic polynomial, eigenvalues, determinant and trace.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] These can therefore serve as isomorphism invariants of graphs.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] However, two graphs may possess the same set of eigenvalues but not be isomorphic.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] Such linear operators are said to be isospectral.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] If A is the adjacency matrix of the directed or undirected graph G, then the matrix *A**n* (i.e., the matrix product of n copies of A) has an interesting interpretation: the element (*i*, *j*) gives the number of (directed or undirected) walks of length n from vertex i to vertex j.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] If n is the smallest nonnegative integer, such that for some i, j, the element (*i*, *j*) of *A**n* is positive, then n is the distance between vertex i and vertex j.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] A great example of how this is useful is in counting the number of triangles in an undirected graph G, which is exactly the trace of *A*3 divided by 3 or 6 depending on whether the graph is directed or not.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] We divide by those values to compensate for the overcounting of each triangle.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] In an undirected graph, each triangle will be counted twice for all three nodes, because the path can be followed clockwise or counterclockwise : ijk or ikj.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] The adjacency matrix can be used to determine whether or not the graph is connected.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] If a directed graph has a nilpotent adjacency matrix (i.e., if there exists n such that *A**n* is the zero matrix), then it is a directed acyclic graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] The adjacency matrix may be used as a data structure for the representation of graphs in computer programs for manipulating graphs.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] Boolean data types are used, such as `True` and `False` in Python.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] The main alternative data structure, also in use for this application, is the adjacency list.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] The space needed to represent an adjacency matrix and the time needed to perform operations on them is dependent on the matrix representation chosen for the underlying matrix.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] Sparse matrix representations only store non-zero matrix entries and implicitly represent the zero entries.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] They can, for example, be used to represent sparse graphs without incurring the space overhead from storing the many zero entries in the adjacency matrix of the sparse graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] In the following section the adjacency matrix is assumed to be represented by an array data structure so that zero and non-zero entries are all directly represented in storage.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] Although slightly more succinct representations are possible, this method gets close to the information-theoretic lower bound for the minimum number of bits needed to represent all n-vertex graphs.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] For storing graphs in text files, fewer bits per byte can be used to ensure that all bytes are text characters, for instance by using a Base64 representation.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] Besides avoiding wasted space, this compactness encourages locality of reference.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] However, for a large sparse graph, adjacency lists require less storage space, because they do not waste any space representing edges that are *not* present.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] An alternative form of adjacency matrix (which, however, requires a larger amount of space) replaces the numbers in each element of the matrix with pointers to edge objects (when edges are present) or null pointers (when there is no edge).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] It is also possible to store edge weights directly in the elements of an adjacency matrix.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] Besides the space tradeoff, the different data structures also facilitate different operations.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] Finding all vertices adjacent to a given vertex in an adjacency list is as simple as reading the list, and takes time proportional to the number of neighbors.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] With an adjacency matrix, an entire row must instead be scanned, which takes a larger amount of time, proportional to the number of vertices in the whole graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/adjacency-matrix] On the other hand, testing whether there is an edge between two given vertices can be determined at once with an adjacency matrix, while requiring time proportional to the minimum degree of the two vertices with the adjacency list.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] In statistics, a **contingency table** (also known as a **cross tabulation** or **crosstab**) is a type of table in a matrix format that displays the multivariate frequency distribution of the variables.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] They are heavily used in survey research, business intelligence, engineering, and scientific research.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] They provide a basic picture of the interrelation between two variables and can help find interactions between them.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] The term *contingency table* was first used by Karl Pearson in "On the Theory of Contingency and Its Relation to Association and Normal Correlation", part of the *Drapers' Company Research Memoirs Biometric Series I* published in 1904.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] A crucial problem of multivariate statistics is finding the (direct-)dependence structure underlying the variables contained in high-dimensional contingency tables.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] If some of the conditional independences are revealed, then even the storage of the data can be done in a smarter way (see Lauritzen (2002)).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] In order to do this one can use information theory concepts, which gain the information only from the distribution of probability, which can be expressed easily from the contingency table by the relative frequencies.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] A pivot table is a way to create contingency tables using spreadsheet software.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] Suppose there are two variables, sex (male or female) and handedness (right- or left-handed).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] Further suppose that 100 individuals are randomly sampled from a very large population as part of a study of sex differences in handedness.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] A contingency table can be created to display the numbers of individuals who are male right-handed and left-handed, female right-handed and left-handed.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] Such a contingency table is shown below.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] The numbers of the males, females, and right- and left-handed individuals are called marginal totals.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] The grand total (the total number of individuals represented in the contingency table) is the number in the bottom right corner.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] The table allows users to see at a glance that the proportion of men who are right-handed is about the same as the proportion of women who are right-handed although the proportions are not identical.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] The strength of the association can be measured by the odds ratio, and the population odds ratio estimated by the sample odds ratio.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] If the proportions of individuals in the different columns vary significantly between rows (or vice versa), it is said that there is a *contingency* between the two variables.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] In other words, the two variables are *not* independent.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] If there is no contingency, it is said that the two variables are *independent*.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] The example above is the simplest kind of contingency table, a table in which each variable has only two levels; this is called a 2 × 2 contingency table.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] In principle, any number of rows and columns may be used.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] There may also be more than two variables, but higher order contingency tables are difficult to represent visually.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] The relation between ordinal variables, or between ordinal and categorical variables, may also be represented in contingency tables, although such a practice is rare.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] For more on the use of a contingency table for the relation between two ordinal variables, see Goodman and Kruskal's gamma.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] The degree of association between the two variables can be assessed by a number of coefficients.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] The following subsections describe a few of them.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] For a more complete discussion of their uses, see the main articles linked under each subsection heading.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] The simplest measure of association for a 2 × 2 contingency table is the odds ratio.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] Given two events, A and B, the odds ratio is defined as the ratio of the odds of A in the presence of B and the odds of A in the absence of B, or equivalently (due to symmetry), the ratio of the odds of B in the presence of A and the odds of B in the absence of A.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] Two events are independent if and only if the odds ratio is 1; if the odds ratio is greater than 1, the events are positively associated; if the odds ratio is less than 1, the events are negatively associated.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] Then its sign equals the sign of the product of the main diagonal elements of the table minus the product of the off–diagonal elements. φ takes on the minimum value −1.0 or the maximum value of +1.0 if and only if every marginal proportion is equal to 0.5 (and two diagonal cells are empty).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] Two alternatives are the *contingency coefficient* *C*, and Cramér's V.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] Another choice is the tetrachoric correlation coefficient but it is only applicable to 2 × 2 tables.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] Polychoric correlation is an extension of the tetrachoric correlation to tables involving variables with more than two levels.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] Tetrachoric correlation assumes that the variable underlying each dichotomous measure is normally distributed.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] The tetrachoric correlation coefficient should not be confused with the Pearson correlation coefficient computed by assigning, say, values 0.0 and 1.0 to represent the two levels of each variable (which is mathematically equivalent to the φ coefficient).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] The lambda coefficient is a measure of the strength of association of the cross tabulations when the variables are measured at the nominal level.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] Values range from 0.0 (no association) to 1.0 (the maximum possible association).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] Asymmetric lambda measures the percentage improvement in predicting the dependent variable.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] Symmetric lambda measures the percentage improvement when prediction is done in both directions.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] The uncertainty coefficient, or Theil's U, is another measure for variables at the nominal level.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] Its values range from −1.0 (100% negative association, or perfect inversion) to +1.0 (100% positive association, or perfect agreement).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] A value of 0.0 indicates the absence of association.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] This asymmetrical property can lead to insights not as evident in symmetrical measures of association.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/contingency-table] Gamma, Tau-b and Tau-c are used when the categories or levels of both variables have a natural order.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] In statistics, **correlation** is a type of statistical relationship between two random variables or bivariate data.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] It usually refers to the extent to which a pair of quantities are linearly related.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] More generally, an arbitrary relationship between variables is called an **association**, meaning the degree to which the variability in one can be accounted for by the other.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] The presence of a correlation is not sufficient to infer the presence of a causal relationship, and this is often stated as "correlation does not imply causation".
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Furthermore, the concept of correlation is not the same as dependence: if two variables are independent, then they are uncorrelated, but the opposite is not necessarily true – even if two variables are uncorrelated, they might be dependent on each other.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Correlations are useful because they can indicate a predictive relationship that can be exploited in practice.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] For example, an electrical utility may produce less power on a mild day based on the correlation between electricity demand and weather.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] In this example, there is a causal relationship, because extreme weather causes people to use more electricity for heating or cooling.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] There are several correlation coefficients that may be used to measure correlation, often denoted $\rho$ or r .
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] The most common of these is the **Pearson correlation coefficient**, which is sensitive only to a linear relationship between two variables (which in turn may be present even when one variable is a nonlinear function of the other).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Other correlation coefficients, such as **Spearman's rank correlation coefficient**, have been developed to be more robust than Pearson's and to detect less structured relationships between variables.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] The concept has been generalized to other forms of association between two variables, such as mutual information and distance covariance.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] The most familiar measure of dependence between two quantities is the Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient, most commonly called 'Pearson's correlation coefficient' or simply 'the correlation coefficient' (as it is the most common variant).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] It is obtained by taking the ratio of the covariance between two variables of a numerical dataset normalized to the square root of their variances.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Equivalently, Pearson's correlation coefficient can be calculated by dividing the covariance of the two variables by the product of their standard deviations.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Karl Pearson developed the coefficient from a similar idea by Francis Galton.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] A Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient attempts to establish a line of best fit through a dataset of two variables by essentially laying out the expected values and the resulting Pearson's correlation coefficient indicates how far away the actual dataset is from the expected values.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Depending on the sign of the Pearson's correlation coefficient, the result can be either a negative or positive correlation if there is any sort of relationship between the variables in the data set.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] where $\operatorname {E}$ is the expected value operator, $\operatorname {cov}$ means covariance, and $\operatorname {corr}$ is a widely used alternative notation for the correlation coefficient.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] The Pearson correlation is defined only if both standard deviations are finite and positive.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] It is a corollary of the Cauchy–Schwarz inequality that the absolute value of the Pearson correlation coefficient is not bigger than 1.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Therefore, the value of a correlation coefficient ranges between −1 and +1.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] As it approaches zero there is less of a relationship (closer to uncorrelated).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] The closer the coefficient is to either −1 or 1, the stronger the correlation between the variables.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] If the variables are independent, Pearson's correlation coefficient is 0.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] However, because the correlation coefficient detects only linear dependencies between two variables, the converse is not necessarily true.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] A correlation coefficient of 0 does not imply that the variables are independent.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] For example, suppose the random variable X is symmetrically distributed about zero, and $Y=X^{2}$ .
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Then Y is completely determined by X , so that X and Y are perfectly dependent, but their correlation is zero; they are uncorrelated.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] However, in the special case when X and Y are jointly normal, uncorrelatedness is equivalent to independence.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Even though uncorrelated data does not necessarily imply independence, one can check if random variables are independent if their mutual information is 0.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Given a series of n measurements of the pair $(X_{i},Y_{i})$ indexed by $i=1,\ldots ,n$ , the *sample correlation coefficient* can be used to estimate the population Pearson correlation $\rho _{X,Y}$ between X and Y .
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] where ${\overline {x}}$ and ${\overline {y}}$ are the sample means of X and Y , and $s_{x}$ and $s_{y}$ are the corrected sample standard deviations of X and Y .
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] where $s'_{x}$ and $s'_{y}$ are the *uncorrected* sample standard deviations of X and Y .
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] If x and y are results of measurements that contain measurement error, the realistic limits on the correlation coefficient are not −1 to +1 but a smaller range.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] For the case of a linear model with a single independent variable, the coefficient of determination (R squared) is the square of $r_{xy}$ , Pearson's product-moment coefficient.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Consider the joint probability distribution of X and Y given in the table below.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Rank correlation coefficients, such as Spearman's rank correlation coefficient and Kendall's rank correlation coefficient (τ) measure the extent to which, as one variable increases, the other variable tends to increase, without requiring that increase to be represented by a linear relationship.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] If, as the one variable increases, the other *decreases*, the rank correlation coefficients will be negative.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] It is common to regard these rank correlation coefficients as alternatives to Pearson's coefficient, used either to reduce the amount of calculation or to make the coefficient less sensitive to non-normality in distributions.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] As we go from each pair to the next pair, x increases, and so does y .
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] This relationship is perfect, in the sense that an increase in x is *always* accompanied by an increase in y .
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] This means that we have a perfect rank correlation, and both Spearman's and Kendall's correlation coefficients are 1, whereas in this example Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient is 0.7544, indicating that the points are far from lying on a straight line.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] In the same way if y always *decreases* when x *increases*, the rank correlation coefficients will be −1, while the Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient may or may not be close to −1, depending on how close the points are to a straight line.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Although in the extreme cases of perfect rank correlation the two coefficients are both equal (being both +1 or both −1), this is not generally the case, and so values of the two coefficients cannot meaningfully be compared.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] For example, for the three pairs (1, 1) (2, 3) (3, 2) Spearman's coefficient is 1/2, while Kendall's coefficient is 1/3.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] The conventional dictum that "correlation does not imply causation" means that correlation cannot be used by itself to infer a causal relationship between the variables.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] This dictum should not be taken to mean that correlations cannot indicate the potential existence of causal relations.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] However, the causes underlying the correlation, if any, may be indirect and unknown, and high correlations also overlap with identity relations (tautologies), where no causal process exists (e.g., between two variables measuring the same construct).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Consequently, a correlation between two variables is not a sufficient condition to establish a causal relationship (in either direction).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] A correlation between age and height in children is fairly causally transparent, but a correlation between mood and health in people is less so.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Does improved mood lead to improved health, or does good health lead to good mood, or both?
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Or does some other factor underlie both?
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] In other words, a correlation can be taken as evidence for a possible causal relationship, but cannot indicate what the causal relationship, if any, might be.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] The Pearson correlation coefficient indicates the strength of a *linear* relationship between two variables, but its value generally does not completely characterize their relationship.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] In particular, if the conditional mean of Y given X , denoted $\operatorname {E} (Y\mid X)$ , is not linear in X , the correlation coefficient will not fully determine the form of $\operatorname {E} (Y\mid X)$ .
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] The adjacent image shows scatter plots of Anscombe's quartet, a set of four different pairs of variables created by Francis Anscombe.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] The four y variables have the same mean (7.5), variance (4.12), correlation (0.816) and regression line ( ${\textstyle y=3+0.5x}$ ).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] However, as can be seen on the plots, the distribution of the variables is very different.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] The first one (top left) seems to be distributed normally, and corresponds to what one would expect when considering two variables correlated and following the assumption of normality.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] The second one (top right) is not distributed normally; while an obvious relationship between the two variables can be observed, it is not linear.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] In this case the Pearson correlation coefficient does not indicate that there is an exact functional relationship: only the extent to which that relationship can be approximated by a linear relationship.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] In the third case (bottom left), the linear relationship is perfect, except for one outlier which exerts enough influence to lower the correlation coefficient from 1 to 0.816.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Finally, the fourth example (bottom right) shows another example when one outlier is enough to produce a high correlation coefficient, even though the relationship between the two variables is not linear.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] These examples indicate that the correlation coefficient, as a summary statistic, cannot replace visual examination of the data.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] The examples are sometimes said to demonstrate that the Pearson correlation assumes that the data follow a normal distribution, but this is only partially correct.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] The Pearson correlation can be accurately calculated for any distribution that has a finite covariance matrix, which includes most distributions encountered in practice.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] However, the Pearson correlation coefficient (taken together with the sample mean and variance) is only a sufficient statistic if the data is drawn from a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] As a result, the Pearson correlation coefficient fully characterizes the relationship between variables if and only if the data are drawn from a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Similarly for two stochastic processes $\left\{X_{t}\right\}_{t\in {\mathcal {T}}}$ and $\left\{Y_{t}\right\}_{t\in {\mathcal {T}}}$ : If they are independent, then they are uncorrelated.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] The opposite of this statement might not be true.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Even if two variables are uncorrelated, they might not be independent of each other.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] The degree of dependence between variables X and Y does not depend on the scale on which the variables are expressed.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] That is, if we are analyzing the relationship between X and Y, most correlation measures are unaffected by transforming X to *a* + *bX* and Y to *c* + *dY*, where *a*, *b*, *c*, and *d* are constants (*b* and *d* being positive).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] This is true of some correlation statistics as well as their population analogues.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Some correlation statistics, such as the rank correlation coefficient, are also invariant to monotone transformations of the marginal distributions of X and/or Y.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Most correlation measures are sensitive to the manner in which X and Y are sampled.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Dependencies tend to be stronger if viewed over a wider range of values.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Several techniques have been developed that attempt to correct for range restriction in one or both variables, and are commonly used in meta-analysis; the most common are Thorndike's case II and case III equations.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Various correlation measures in use may be undefined for certain joint distributions of X and Y.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] For example, the Pearson correlation coefficient is defined in terms of moments, and hence will be undefined if the moments are undefined.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Measures of dependence based on quantiles are always defined.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Sample-based statistics intended to estimate population measures of dependence may or may not have desirable statistical properties such as being unbiased, or asymptotically consistent, based on the spatial structure of the population from which the data were sampled.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Sensitivity to the data distribution can be used to an advantage.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] For example, scaled correlation is designed to use the sensitivity to the range in order to pick out correlations between fast components of time series.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] By reducing the range of values in a controlled manner, the correlations on long time scale are filtered out and only the correlations on short time scales are revealed.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Thus the diagonal entries are all identically one.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] If the measures of correlation used are product-moment coefficients, the correlation matrix is the same as the covariance matrix of the standardized random variables $X_{i}/\sigma (X_{i})$ for $i=1,\dots ,n$ .
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] This applies both to the matrix of population correlations (in which case $\sigma$ is the population standard deviation), and to the matrix of sample correlations (in which case $\sigma$ denotes the sample standard deviation).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Consequently, each is necessarily a positive-semidefinite matrix.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Moreover, the correlation matrix is strictly positive definite if no variable can have all its values exactly generated as a linear function of the values of the others.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] The correlation matrix is symmetric because the correlation between $X_{i}$ and $X_{j}$ is the same as the correlation between $X_{j}$ and $X_{i}$ .
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] A correlation matrix appears, for example, in one formula for the coefficient of multiple determination, a measure of goodness of fit in multiple regression.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] In statistical modelling, correlation matrices representing the relationships between variables are categorized into different correlation structures, which are distinguished by factors such as the number of parameters required to estimate them.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] For example, in an exchangeable correlation matrix, all pairs of variables are modeled as having the same correlation, so all non-diagonal elements of the matrix are equal to each other.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] On the other hand, an autoregressive matrix is often used when variables represent a time series, since correlations are likely to be greater when measurements are closer in time.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Other examples include independent, unstructured, M-dependent, and Toeplitz.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] In exploratory data analysis, the iconography of correlations consists in replacing a correlation matrix by a diagram where the "remarkable" correlations are represented by a solid line (positive correlation), or a dotted line (negative correlation).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] In some applications (e.g., building data models from only partially observed data) one wants to find the "nearest" correlation matrix to an "approximate" correlation matrix (e.g., a matrix which typically lacks positive semi-definiteness due to the way it has been computed).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] In 2002, Higham formalized the notion of nearness using the Frobenius norm and provided a method for computing the nearest correlation matrix using the Dykstra's projection algorithm.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] This sparked interest in the subject, with new theoretical (e.g., computing the nearest correlation matrix with factor structure) and numerical (e.g. usage of Newton's method for computing the nearest correlation matrix) results obtained in the subsequent years.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] where $\operatorname {\boldsymbol {\mathcal {E}}} (X)$ and $\operatorname {\boldsymbol {\mathcal {E}}} (Y)$ are the expected values of $\ X\$ and $\ Y\ ,$ respectively, and $\ \sigma _{X}\$ and $\ \sigma _{Y}\$ are the standard deviations of $\ X\$ and $\ Y\ ,$ respectively.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] where $\ F_{Hyp}\$ is the Gaussian hypergeometric function.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] This density is both a Bayesian posterior density and an exact optimal confidence distribution density.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] The information given by a correlation coefficient is not enough to define the dependence structure between random variables.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] The correlation coefficient completely defines the dependence structure only in very particular cases, for example when the distribution is a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] (See diagram above.) In the case of elliptical distributions it characterizes the (hyper-)ellipses of equal density; however, it does not completely characterize the dependence structure (for example, a multivariate t-distribution's degrees of freedom determine the level of tail dependence).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] For continuous variables, multiple alternative measures of dependence were introduced to address the deficiency of Pearson's correlation that it can be zero for dependent random variables (see and references therein for an overview).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] They all share the important property that a value of zero implies independence.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] This led some authors to recommend their routine usage, particularly of distance correlation.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Another alternative measure is the Randomized Dependence Coefficient.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] The RDC is a computationally efficient, copula-based measure of dependence between multivariate random variables and is invariant with respect to non-linear scalings of random variables.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] One important disadvantage of the alternative, more general measures is that, when used to test whether two variables are associated, they tend to have lower power compared to Pearson's correlation when the data follow a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] This is an implication of the No free lunch theorem.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] To detect all kinds of relationships, these measures have to sacrifice power on other relationships, particularly for the important special case of a linear relationship with Gaussian marginals, for which Pearson's correlation is optimal.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Another problem concerns interpretation.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] While Pearson's correlation can be interpreted for all values, the alternative measures can generally only be interpreted meaningfully at the extremes.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] For two binary variables, the odds ratio measures their dependence, and takes a range of non-negative numbers, possibly infinity: ⁠ $[0,+\infty ]$ ⁠.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] Related statistics such as Yule's *Y* and Yule's *Q* normalize this to the correlation-like range ⁠ $[-1,1]$ ⁠.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/correlation] The odds ratio is generalized by the logistic model to model cases where the dependent variables are discrete and there may be one or more independent variables.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] In mathematics and computer science, **graph theory** is the study of graphs, which are mathematical structures used to model pairwise relations between objects.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] A graph in this context is made up of vertices (also called nodes or points) which are connected by edges (also called arcs, links, or lines).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] A distinction is made between undirected graphs, where edges link two vertices symmetrically, and directed graphs, where edges link two vertices asymmetrically.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Graphs are one of the principal objects of study in discrete mathematics.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Graph theory is a branch of mathematics that studies graphs, mathematical structures for modelling pairwise relations between objects.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] It is part of discrete mathematics, often considered part of combinatorics, although it is a stand-alone field due to its great growth and distinct from other fields, having its own kind of problems.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The term "graph" was introduced by James Joseph Sylvester in a paper published in 1878 in *Nature*, where he drew an analogy between "quantic invariants" and "co-variants" of algebra and molecular diagrams.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The definition of a graph can vary, but one can understand that a graph is a structure consisting of vertices (also called nodes or points) and edges (also called arcs, links, or lines).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Two vertices of an edge are called the endpoints.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Occasionally, a graph is called an undirected graph, to distinguish it from a directed graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] A directed graph is a graph where each edge has an assignment direction known as orientation, designated with an arrow.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] A mixed graph can have edges that may be directed, and some may be undirected.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] A graph can also be called a simple graph, to distinguish it from a multigraph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] A multigraph allows many edges to have the same pair of endpoints, and it also allows an edge to connect a vertex to itself, known as a loop.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] A graph can have its edges assigned a number, which is known as the weight.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Such a graph is called a weighted graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] In 1736, Leonhard Euler published a paper titled *Solutio Problematis ad Geometriam Situs Pertinentis* on the Seven Bridges of Königsberg, which is regarded as the first paper in the history of graph theory.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Euler's paper and Alexandre-Théophile Vandermonde's 1771 *Remarques sur les Problèmes de Situation* paper on the knight's tour carried on with the *analysis situs*, initiated by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Euler's characteristic relating the number of edges, vertices, and faces of a convex polyhedron was studied and generalized by Augustin-Louis Cauchy and Simon Antoine Jean L'Huilier, and represents the beginning of the branch of mathematics known as topology.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] More than one century after Euler's paper on the bridges of Königsberg, and while Johann Benedict Listing was introducing the concept of topology, Arthur Cayley was led by an interest in particular analytical forms arising from differential calculus to study a particular class of graphs, the trees.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] This study had many implications for theoretical chemistry.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The techniques he used mainly concern the enumeration of graphs with particular properties.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Enumerative graph theory then arose from the results of Cayley and the fundamental results published by Pólya between 1935 and 1937.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] These were generalized by Nicolaas Govert de Bruijn in 1959.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Cayley linked his results on trees with contemporary studies of chemical composition.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The fusion of ideas from mathematics with those from chemistry began what has become part of the standard terminology of graph theory.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The autonomous development of topology from 1860 to 1930 fertilized graph theory back through the works of Camille Jordan, Kazimierz Kuratowski, and Hassler Whitney.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Another important factor in the common development of graph theory and topology came from the use of the techniques of modern algebra.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The first example of such a use comes from the work of the physicist Gustav Kirchhoff, who published in 1845 his Kirchhoff's circuit laws for calculating the voltage and current in electric circuits.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The first textbook on graph theory was written by Dénes Kőnig, and published in 1936.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Another book by Frank Harary, published in 1969, was "considered the world over to be the definitive textbook on the subject", and enabled mathematicians, chemists, electrical engineers and social scientists to talk to each other.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Harary donated all of the royalties to fund the Pólya Prize.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] One of the most famous problems in graph theory is the four color problem: Is it true that any map drawn in the plane may have its regions colored with four colors, in such a way that any two regions having a common border have different colors?
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] This problem was first posed by Francis Guthrie in 1852, and its first written record is in a letter of Augustus De Morgan addressed to William Rowan Hamilton the same year.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Many incorrect proofs have been proposed, including those by Augustin Cayley, Alfred Kempe, and others.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The study and the generalization of this problem by Peter Tait, Percy John Heawood, Frank P.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Ramsey and Hadwiger led to the study of the colorings of the graphs embedded on surfaces with arbitrary genus.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Tait's reformulation generated a new class of problems, the *factorization problems*, particularly studied by Petersen and Dénes Kőnig.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The works of Ramsey on colorations, and more specially, the results obtained by Pál Turán in 1941, were at the origin of another branch of graph theory, known as extremal graph theory.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The four-color problem remained unsolved for more than a century.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] In 1969, Heinrich Heesch published a method for solving the problem using computers.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] A computer-aided proof produced in 1976 by Kenneth Appel and Wolfgang Haken makes fundamental use of the notion of "discharging" developed by Heesch.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The proof involved checking the properties of 1,936 configurations by computer, and was not fully accepted at the time due to its complexity.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] A simpler proof considering only 633 configurations was given twenty years later by Robertson, Seymour, Sanders and Thomas.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The introduction of probabilistic methods in graph theory, especially in the study of Erdős and Rényi of the asymptotic probability of graph connectivity, gave rise to yet another branch, known as random graph theory, which has been a fruitful source of graph-theoretic results.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Topological graph theory deals with the study of graphs related to topology.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Topological graph theory deals with the study of graphs as topological spaces.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The graph in a topology is a set of simplexes that is called the simplicial one-dimensional complex.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] This subarea studies the embedding (or imbedding) of a graph in surface and linkless embedding, graph minors, crossing number, map coloring, and voltage graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The embedding of a graph in a surface is the representation of a graph in which the points are associated with the vertices and simple arcs with edges in a surface.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The endpoints are associated with an edge, and the points with the end vertices.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] No arcs include points associated with other vertices, and two arcs never intersect at a point that is interior to either of the arcs.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The graph embedding can be generalized into the linkless embedding, whereby no two cycles of the graph are linked in three-dimensional Euclidean space, and a book, a collection of half-planes all having the same line as their boundary.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The graph is said to be minor if it can be formed from another graph by deleting vertices and edges, and by edge-contraction.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The earliest result of the graph minor theory is from Wagner's theorem, stating that a finite graph is planar if and only if its minor includes neither the complete graph on five vertices $K_{5}$ nor the utility graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] A related result is the Robertson–Seymour theorem, implying the existence of forbidden minor for every property of graphs preserved by deletions and edge contractions.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The crossing number tells the minimum number of crossing edges of a graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] This study originated from a Hungarian mathematician Pál Turán who asked for a factory plan that minimized the number of crossings between tracks connecting brick kilns to storage sites.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] This problem can be formalized as asking for the crossing number of a complete bipartite graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] A graph coloring is a methodical assignment of labelling the elements of a graph, which is traditionally called colors.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] In coloring, no two adjacent elements have the same color.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] It requires the minimum number of colors, which is known as the chromatic number.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Four-color theorem stated that no more than four colors are required to color the regions of any map so that no two adjacent regions have the same color; that is, no two regions share a common boundary.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] This theorem is stronger than five-color theorem.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Relatedly, Earth–Moon problem is known for the nowadays open problem on extension of the planar map coloring problem, solved by the four-color theorem.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] A voltage graph is a directed graph whose edges are labelled invertibly by elements of a group.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] This graph concisely specifies the derived graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] It is also a common way to form a covering graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Algebraic graph theory is the study of graph theory that involves major branches of algebra.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Major branches of algebra that are used are linear algebra and group theory.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] A study of graph theory using linear algebra is called spectral graph theory.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] This study focuses on adjacency matrix, a matrix that represents the graph, and its spectrum, which focuses on the characteristic polynomial, eigenvalues, and eigenvectors of the given adjacency matrix.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] It also focuses on the Laplacian matrix of a graph, which involves the degree matrix (a diagonal matrix that represents the degree of a vertex) and the adjacency matrix.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Group theory, particularly automorphism groups and geometric group theory, focuses on various families of graphs based on symmetry in algebraic graph theory.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Such a symmetry includes symmetric graphs, vertex-transitive graphs, edge-transitive graphs, distance-transitive graphs, distance-regular graphs, and strongly regular graphs.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Frucht's theorem states that every finite group is the group of symmetries of a finite undirected graph, or more strongly, there exist infinitely many non-isomorphic simple connected graphs such that the automorphism group of each of them is isomorphic to a finite group.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Algebraic graph theory also studies the algebraic invariants, chromatic polynomial, Tutte polynomial of a graph, and knot invariant.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] A graph invariant is a property of graphs that depends only on the abstract structure, instead of labellings or drawings of the graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] A chromatic polynomial is a polynomial that counts the number of graph colorings as a function of the number of colors.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The Tutte polynomial is a two-variable polynomial on graph connectivity.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Geometric graph theory studies a graph drawn with straight-line or continuous curved edges with geometric properties combinatorially.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Geometric graph theory focuses on combinatorial and geometric properties of a graph that is drawn in a plane with straight-line or continuous curved edges in Euclidean space.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] As part of discrete geometry and computational geometry, geometric graph theory studies planar graphs, relationship to higher-dimensional convex polytopes, intersection of geometrical shaped sets, and other geometries' subareas of incidence geometry and projective geometry.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] A planar graph wherein its vertices are embedded as points, and its edges are non-crossing line segments in the Euclidean plane is called planar straight-line graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Any planar graph can be represented as a planar straight-line graph by Fáry's theorem.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The planar straight-line graph is the special case of a Euclidean graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The Euclidean graph allows its edges to have the length of the Euclidean distance between its endpoints.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] A visibility graph is a graph whose vertices and edges are the point locations and visible connections, respectively.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] In a simple polygon, where its edges are not self-intersecting and have no holes, the vertices of a visibility graph are connected by edges that represent the sides and diagonals of a polygon.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The vertices are defined as the point locations.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Polyhedral graph is an undirected graph that forms the vertices and edges of a three-dimensional convex polyhedron.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] In order to achieve it, such a graph must meet the requirements of Steinitz's theorem, stating that every convex polyhedron is 3-vertex connected planar graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The planar graph remains connected whenever any two of its vertices are removed.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] An intersection graph is a graph in which each vertex is associated with a set and in which vertices are connected by edges whenever the corresponding sets have a nonempty intersection.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Each vertex is represented as a set, and every two vertices are connected.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Hence, the intersection graph of finite sets can be represented through the smallest number of required elements, known as the intersection number.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The result graph can be geometric whenever the sets are geometrical objects.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] For instance, the intersection graph of line segments in one dimension is an interval graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The intersection graph of unit disks in the plane is a unit disk graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The intersection of a circle packing is a coin graph, where a vertex and an edge represent a circle and every pair of tangent circles; by Koebe–Andreev–Thurston theorem, the intersection graphs of non-crossing circles are exactly the planar graphs.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Scheinerman's theorem states that every planar graph can be represented as the intersection graph of line segments in the plane.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The Levi graph is a bipartite graph that associates to the incidence structure and projective configuration.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] By applying to information visualization, this creates another subarea of graph theory that is known as graph drawing, which visualizes a graph depiction.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Frequently drawn as node–link diagrams, the vertices of a graph are represented as disks, boxes, or textual labels, and the edges are represented as line segments, polylines, or curves in the Euclidean plane.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Many definitions for graph drawings based on quality measures include the crossing number, area, symmetry display on finding the problem of a graph's group automorphism, bend minimization, angular resolution, and slope number.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Tools for graph drawings are the circle packing, the intersection graph, and other visualizations of the adjacency matrix.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Extremal graph theory is a branch of mathematics at the intersection of extremal combinatorics and graph theory.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] This area studies the maximum number of a graph's edges, known as the extremal number.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The subarea's milestone originated from Mantel's theorem on the extremal number of a triangle-free graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Turán's theorem extended Mantel's theorem for any undirected graph that does not have a complete subgraph of a given size.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Turán's theorem is generalized by Erdős–Stone theorem, which is occasionally known as the "fundamental theorem of extremal graph theory".
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Extremal graph theory also studies forbidden subgraph problem, homomorphism density, and Szemerédi regularity lemma.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The forbidden subgraphs problem suggests finding the extremal number of a graph with n vertices such that it does not have a subgraph that is isomorphic to the graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] A homomorphism density is a parameter that involves the graph homomorphism.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The density may refer to the probability that a map from the vertices of a graph to the vertices of another one chosen uniformly at random is a graph homomorphism.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Being homomorphic means there exists a mapping between two graphs that respects their structure, or equivalently, a function between the vertex sets of two graphs that maps adjacent vertices to adjacent vertices.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Szemerédi's regularity lemma states that a graph can be partitioned into a bounded number of parts so that the edges between parts are $\varepsilon$ -regular.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The theory of random graph focuses on graphs using probabilistic method.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The subarea was founded by Hungarian mathematicians Paul Erdős and Alfréd Rényi, whose modelling generates random graphs, known as Erdős–Rényi model.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] A tree is an undirected graph where every pair of vertices is connected by exactly one path.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Therefore, a random tree is a tree that is formed by a stochastic process.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Graphs can be used to model many types of relations and processes in physical, biological, social and information systems.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Many practical problems can be represented by graphs.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Emphasizing their application to real-world systems, the term *network* is sometimes defined to mean a graph in which attributes (e.g. names) are associated with the vertices and edges, and the subject that expresses and understands real-world systems as a network is called network science.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Within computer science, 'causal' and 'non-causal' linked structures are graphs that are used to represent networks of communication, data organization, computational devices, the flow of computation, etc.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] For instance, the link structure of a website can be represented by a directed graph, in which the vertices (nodes) represent web pages and directed edges represent links from one page to another.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] A similar approach can be taken to problems in social media, travel, biology, computer chip design, mapping the progression of neuro-degenerative diseases, and many other fields.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The development of algorithms to handle graphs is therefore of major interest in computer science.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The transformation of graphs is often formalized and represented by graph rewrite systems.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Complementary to graph transformation systems focusing on rule-based in-memory manipulation of graphs are graph databases geared towards transaction-safe, persistent storing and querying of graph-structured data.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Graph-theoretic methods, in various forms, have proven particularly useful in linguistics, since natural language often lends itself well to discrete structure.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Traditionally, syntax and compositional semantics follow tree-based structures, whose expressive power lies in the principle of compositionality, modeled in a hierarchical graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] More contemporary approaches such as head-driven phrase structure grammar model the syntax of natural language using typed feature structures, which are directed acyclic graphs.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Within lexical semantics, especially as applied to computers, modeling word meaning is easier when a given word is understood in terms of related words; semantic networks are therefore important in computational linguistics.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Still, other methods in phonology (e.g. optimality theory, which uses lattice graphs) and morphology (e.g. finite-state morphology, using finite-state transducers) are common in the analysis of language as a graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Indeed, the usefulness of this area of mathematics to linguistics has borne organizations such as TextGraphs, as well as various 'Net' projects, such as WordNet, VerbNet, and others.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Graph theory is also used to study molecules in chemistry and physics.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] In condensed matter physics, the three-dimensional structure of complicated simulated atomic structures can be studied quantitatively by gathering statistics on graph-theoretic properties related to the topology of the atoms.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Also, "the Feynman graphs and rules of calculation summarize quantum field theory in a form in close contact with the experimental numbers one wants to understand." In chemistry a graph makes a natural model for a molecule, where vertices represent atoms and edges bonds.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] This approach is especially used in computer processing of molecular structures, ranging from chemical editors to database searching.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] In statistical physics, graphs can represent local connections between interacting parts of a system, as well as the dynamics of a physical process on such systems.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Similarly, in computational neuroscience graphs can be used to represent functional connections between brain areas that interact to give rise to various cognitive processes, where the vertices represent different areas of the brain and the edges represent the connections between those areas.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Graph theory plays an important role in electrical modeling of electrical networks, here, weights are associated with resistance of the wire segments to obtain electrical properties of network structures.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Graphs are also used to represent the micro-scale channels of porous media, in which the vertices represent the pores and the edges represent the smaller channels connecting the pores.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Chemical graph theory uses the molecular graph as a means to model molecules.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Graphs and networks are excellent models to study and understand phase transitions and critical phenomena.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Removal of nodes or edges leads to a critical transition where the network breaks into small clusters which is studied as a phase transition.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] This breakdown is studied via percolation theory.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Graph theory is also widely used in sociology as a way, for example, to measure actors' prestige or to explore rumor spreading, notably through the use of social network analysis software.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Under the umbrella of social networks are many different types of graphs.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Acquaintanceship and friendship graphs describe whether people know each other.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Influence graphs model whether certain people can influence the behavior of others.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Finally, collaboration graphs model whether two people work together in a particular way, such as acting in a movie together.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Likewise, graph theory is useful in biology and conservation efforts where a vertex can represent regions where certain species exist (or inhabit) and the edges represent migration paths or movement between the regions.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] This information is important when looking at breeding patterns or tracking the spread of disease, parasites or how changes to the movement can affect other species.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Graphs are also commonly used in molecular biology and genomics to model and analyze datasets with complex relationships.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] For example, graph-based methods are often used to 'cluster' cells together into cell-types in single-cell transcriptome analysis.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Another use is to model genes or proteins in a pathway and study the relationships between them, such as metabolic pathways and gene regulatory networks.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Evolutionary trees, ecological networks, and hierarchical clustering of gene expression patterns are also represented as graph structures.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Graph theory is also used in connectomics; nervous systems can be seen as a graph, where the nodes are neurons and the edges are the connections between them.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] A graph structure can be extended by assigning a weight to each edge of the graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Graphs with weights, or weighted graphs, are used to represent structures in which pairwise connections have some numerical values.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] For example, if a graph represents a road network, the weights could represent the length of each road.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] There may be several weights associated with each edge, including distance (as in the previous example), travel time, or monetary cost.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Such weighted graphs are commonly used to program GPS's, and travel-planning search engines that compare flight times and costs.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] A graph is an abstraction of relationships that emerge in nature; hence, it cannot be coupled to a certain representation.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The way it is represented depends on the degree of convenience such representation provides for a certain application.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The most common representations are the visual, in which, usually, vertices are drawn and connected by edges, and the tabular, in which rows of a table provide information about the relationships between the vertices within the graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Graphs are usually represented visually by drawing a point or circle for every vertex, and drawing a line between two vertices if they are connected by an edge.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] If the graph is directed, the direction is indicated by drawing an arrow.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] If the graph is weighted, the weight is added on the arrow.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] A graph drawing should not be confused with the graph itself (the abstract, non-visual structure) as there are several ways to structure the graph drawing.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] All that matters is which vertices are connected to which others by how many edges and not the exact layout.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] In practice, it is often difficult to decide if two drawings represent the same graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Depending on the problem domain some layouts may be better suited and easier to understand than others.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Tutte was very influential on the subject of graph drawing.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Among other achievements, he introduced the use of linear algebraic methods to obtain graph drawings.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Graph drawing also can be said to encompass problems that deal with the crossing number and its various generalizations.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The crossing number of a graph is the minimum number of intersections between edges that a drawing of the graph in the plane must contain.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] For a planar graph, the crossing number is zero by definition.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Drawings on surfaces other than the plane are also studied.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] There are other techniques to visualize a graph away from vertices and edges, including circle packings, intersection graph, and other visualizations of the adjacency matrix.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The tabular representation lends itself well to computational applications.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] There are different ways to store graphs in a computer system.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The data structure used depends on both the graph structure and the algorithm used for manipulating the graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Theoretically one can distinguish between list and matrix structures but in concrete applications the best structure is often a combination of both.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] List structures are often preferred for sparse graphs as they have smaller memory requirements.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Matrix structures on the other hand provide faster access for some applications but can consume huge amounts of memory.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Implementations of sparse matrix structures that are efficient on modern parallel computer architectures are an object of current investigation.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] List structures include the edge list, an array of pairs of vertices, and the adjacency list, which separately lists the neighbors of each vertex: Much like the edge list, each vertex has a list of which vertices it is adjacent to.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Matrix structures include the incidence matrix, a matrix of 0's and 1's whose rows represent vertices and whose columns represent edges, and the adjacency matrix, in which both the rows and columns are indexed by vertices.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] In both cases a 1 indicates two adjacent objects and a 0 indicates two non-adjacent objects.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The degree matrix indicates the degree of vertices.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The Laplacian matrix is a modified form of the adjacency matrix that incorporates information about the degrees of the vertices, and is useful in some calculations such as Kirchhoff's theorem on the number of spanning trees of a graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The distance matrix, like the adjacency matrix, has both its rows and columns indexed by vertices, but rather than containing a 0 or a 1 in each cell it contains the length of a shortest path between two vertices.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] There is a large literature on graphical enumeration: the problem of counting graphs meeting specified conditions.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Some of this work is found in Harary and Palmer (1973).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] A common problem, called the subgraph isomorphism problem, is finding a fixed graph as a subgraph in a given graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] One reason to be interested in such a question is that many graph properties are *hereditary* for subgraphs, which means that a graph has the property if and only if all subgraphs have it too.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Finding maximal subgraphs of a certain kind is often an NP-complete problem.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] One special case of subgraph isomorphism is the graph isomorphism problem.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] It asks whether two graphs are isomorphic.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] It is not known whether this problem is NP-complete, nor whether it can be solved in polynomial time.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] A similar problem is finding induced subgraphs in a given graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Again, some important graph properties are hereditary with respect to induced subgraphs, which means that a graph has a property if and only if all induced subgraphs also have it.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Finding maximal induced subgraphs of a certain kind is also often NP-complete.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Still another such problem, the minor containment problem, is to find a fixed graph as a minor of a given graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] A minor or subcontraction of a graph is any graph obtained by taking a subgraph and contracting some (or no) edges.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Many graph properties are hereditary for minors, which means that a graph has a property if and only if all minors have it too.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] A similar problem, the subdivision containment problem, is to find a fixed graph as a subdivision of a given graph.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] A subdivision or homeomorphism of a graph is any graph obtained by subdividing some (or no) edges.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Subdivision containment is related to graph properties such as planarity.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Another class of problems has to do with the extent to which various species and generalizations of graphs are determined by their *point-deleted subgraphs*.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Many problems and theorems in graph theory have to do with various ways of coloring graphs.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Typically, one is interested in coloring a graph so that no two adjacent vertices have the same color, or with other similar restrictions.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] One may also consider coloring edges (possibly so that no two coincident edges are the same color), or other variations.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Constraint modeling theories concern families of directed graphs related by a partial order.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] In these applications, graphs are ordered by specificity, meaning that more constrained graphs—which are more specific and thus contain a greater amount of information—are subsumed by those that are more general.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Operations between graphs include evaluating the direction of a subsumption relationship between two graphs, if any, and computing graph unification.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] The unification of two argument graphs is defined as the most general graph (or the computation thereof) that is consistent with (i.e. contains all of the information in) the inputs, if such a graph exists; efficient unification algorithms are known.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] For constraint frameworks which are strictly compositional, graph unification is the sufficient satisfiability and combination function.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Well-known applications include automatic theorem proving and modeling the elaboration of linguistic structure.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Covering problems in graphs may refer to various set cover problems on subsets of vertices/subgraphs.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Decomposition, defined as partitioning the edge set of a graph (with as many vertices as necessary accompanying the edges of each part of the partition), has a wide variety of questions.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Often, the problem is to decompose a graph into subgraphs isomorphic to a fixed graph; for instance, decomposing a complete graph into Hamiltonian cycles.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Other problems specify a family of graphs into which a given graph should be decomposed, for instance, a family of cycles, or decomposing a complete graph *K**n* into *n* − 1 specified trees having, respectively, 1, 2, 3, ..., *n* − 1 edges.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/graph-theory] Many problems involve characterizing the members of various classes of graphs.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] A **heat map** (or **heatmap**) is a two-dimensional data visualization technique that represents the magnitude of individual values within a dataset as a color.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] The variation in color may be by hue or intensity.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] In some applications such as crime analytics or website click-tracking, color is used to represent the *density* of data points rather than a value associated with each point.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] "Heat map" is a relatively new term, but the practice of shading matrices has existed for over a century.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Heat maps originated in 2D displays of the values in a data matrix.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Larger values were represented by small dark gray or black squares (pixels) and smaller values by lighter squares.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] The earliest known example dates to 1873, when Toussaint Loua used a hand-drawn and colored shaded matrix to visualize social statistics across the districts of Paris.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] The idea of reordering rows and columns to reveal structure in a data matrix, known as seriation, was introduced by Flinders Petrie in 1899.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] In 1950, Louis Guttman developed the Scalogram, a method for ordering binary matrices to expose a one-dimensional scale structure.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] In 1957, Peter Sneath displayed the results of a cluster analysis by permuting the rows and the columns of a matrix to place similar values near each other according to the clustering.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] This idea was implemented by Robert Ling in 1973 with a computer program called SHADE.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Ling used overstruck printer characters to represent different shades of gray, one character-width per pixel.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Leland Wilkinson developed the first computer program in 1994 (SYSTAT) to produce cluster heat maps with high-resolution color graphics.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] The Eisen et al. display shown in the figure is a replication of the earlier SYSTAT design.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Software designer Cormac Kinney trademarked the term 'heat map' in 1991 to describe computer software used to display real-time financial market information.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] In 1998 the trademark was acquired by SS&C Technologies, Inc., but the company did not extend the license, so it was annulled in 2006.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] There are two primary categories of heat maps: spatial and grid.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Additionally, there are over ten various types of heat maps.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] A **spatial heat map** displays the magnitude of a spatial phenomenon as color, usually cast over a map.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] In the image labeled "Spatial Heat Map Example," temperature is displayed by color range across a map of the world.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Color ranges from blue (cold) to red (hot).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] A **grid heat map** displays magnitude as color in a two-dimensional matrix, with each dimension representing a category of trait and the color representing the magnitude of some measurement on the combined traits from each of the two categories.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] For example, one dimension might represent year, and the other dimension might represent month, and the value measured might be temperature.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] This heat map would show how temperature changed over the years in each month.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Grid heat maps are further categorized into two different types of matrices: clustered, and correlogram.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] In a grid heat map, colors are presented in a grid of a fixed size, with every cell in the grid also being an equal size and shape.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] The goal is to detect clustering, or suggest the presence of clusters.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] A spatial heat map is often used on maps or satellite imagery (see GIS), where there is no concept of cells, and instead the colors vary continuously.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Heat maps have a wide range of possibilities amongst applications due to their ability to simplify data and make for visually appealing to read data analysis.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Many applications using different types of heat maps are listed below.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Business Analysis: Heat maps are used in business analytics to give a visual representation about a company's current functioning, performance, and the need for improvements.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Heat maps are a way to analyze a company's existing data and update it to reflect growth and other specific efforts.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Heat maps visually appeal to team members and clients of the business or company.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Websites: There are many different ways heat maps are used within websites to determine a visiting users actions.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Typically, there are multiple heat maps used together to determine insight to a website on what are the best and worst performing elements on the page.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Some specific heat maps used for website analysis are listed below.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Exploratory Data Analysis: Working with small and large data sets, data scientists and data analysts look at and determine essential relationships and characteristics amongst different points in a data set as well as features of those data points.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Data scientists and analysts work with a team of others in different professions.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] The use of heat maps make for a visually easy way to summarize findings and main components.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] There are other ways to represent data, however heat maps can visualize these data points and their relationships in a high dimensional space without becoming too compact and visually unappealing.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Heat maps in data analysis, allow for specific variables of rows and/or columns on the axes and even on the diagonal.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Biology: In the biological field, heat maps are used to visually represent large and small sets of data.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] The focus is towards patterns and similarities in DNA, RNA, gene expression, etc.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Financial Analysis: The values of different product and assets fluctuate both rapidly and/or gradually over time.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] The need to log changes to the daily markets is imperative.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] It allows for the ability to draw predictions from patterns while being able to revisit past numerical data.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Heat maps are able to remove the tedious process and enable the user to visualize data points and compare amongst the different performers.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Geographical Visualization: Heat maps are used to visualize and display a geographic distribution of data.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Heat maps represent different densities of data points on a geographical map to help users see the intensities of certain phenomena and to show items of most or least importance.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Heat maps used in geographical visualization are sometimes confused with choropleth maps, but the difference comes with how certain data is presented which differentiate the two.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Sports: Heat maps can be used in many sports and can influence manager's and/or coaches decisions based on high and low densities of data displayed.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Users can identify patterns within the game, the strategies of opponents and one's own team, make more informed decisions benefitting the player, team, and business, and can enhance performance in different areas by identifying enhancement is needed.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Heat maps also visualize comparisons and relationships amongst different teams in the same sport or between different sports all together.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Cybersecurity: In intrusion detection systems and log analysis, heat maps are used to highlight unusual access patterns, port scanning attempts, and malicious IP clustering.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] They help SOC (Security Operations Center) analysts quickly spot anomalies in large datasets.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Urban Planning: Heat maps are used in urban planning to visualize traffic congestion, pedestrian flow, and environmental conditions for data-driven infrastructure development (Batty et al., 2012).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Environmental heat maps track air quality and urban heat islands, guiding green space planning (EEA, 2021).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Noise pollution heat maps aid zoning and mitigation near residential areas (EEA, 2020).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Commercial planners use foot traffic heat maps to optimize retail layouts (SmartSantander, 2014).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Integrated in smart city systems, these maps enhance livability, sustainability, and safety (Batty et al., 2012).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Many different color schemes can be used to illustrate the heat map, with perceptual advantages and disadvantages for each.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Choosing a good color scheme is integral to accurately and effectively displaying data, whereas a poor color scheme can lead viewers to inaccurate conclusions or exclude those with color deficiencies from proper analysis of said data.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Rainbow color maps, while a common choice, suffer from both accessibility and data continuity concerns.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Rainbow maps pose a challenge for users with color vision deficiencies, particularly in those with issues distinguishing red and green – a condition affecting a significant portion of the population.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] In addition to accessibility issues, rainbow heat map colors are not perceptually uniform; equal increments in data values do not correspond to equal changes in color.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] The lack of uniformity can create misleading visual effects, like an artificial boundary or gradient.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] These effects can compromise the accuracy of effectiveness of the visualization.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] This example of the amplitude with the colors showcasing the phase angle can be hard to interpret with the entire rainbow of colors.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] In this case, the rainbow color scheme may cloud interpretation for those with color vision deficiencies or create confusion by some of the hard color boundaries across the diagram.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] To address these challenges, perceptually uniform color sets have been created to accommodate visual impairments and maintain consistent color differences proportional to differences in data.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Perceptually uniform color schemes are carefully designed to maintain consistent perceptual differences and offer a better viewing experience for viewers with color vision deficiencies.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] When implementing these color schemes into a heat map, designers must consider the data context and intended emphasis.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] These schemes follow three main patterns: sequential gradients (varying intensity of a single hue), diverging palettes (two contrasting hues with a neutral midpoint), and qualitative sets for categorical data.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Scientific visualization has produced several perceptually uniform color sets (like Viridis, Magma, and Cividis) that address both uniformity and accessibility concerns.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Device limitations can also significantly affect heat map visualization effectiveness.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] When displayed on low-resolution screens, highly detailed color gradients may appear pixelated or banded, reducing the quality of the visualization; this is known as color quantization, which can obscure or wrongly emphasize pieces of data.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] To mitigate these effects, designers should consider all devices that will display their heat map, and their color limitations.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Comprehensive testing and using a scheme with few colors is the safest bet when creating a heat map that will be viewed across multiple device types.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Grey-scale compatibility is essential for heat map accessibility, especially when considering print media, black and white only displays, or monochromatic vision.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] When converting to grey-scale, many color schemes will lose their distinctive data mappings, allowing for different values to appear identical in luminescence.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Grey-scale friendly color schemes are designed to incorporate contrast between data points even when color is removed, such as the "virdis" family.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Choropleth maps and heat maps are often used in place of one another incorrectly when referring to data visualized geographically.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Both techniques show the proportion of a variable of interest, but the two differ in how the boundaries for the variable's data aggregations are constructed.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] If the data were collected and aggregated using irregular boundaries, such as administrative units, then a heat map displaying that data will be the same as a choropleth map, encouraging confusion about how the two differ.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Choropleth maps show data grouped by geographic boundaries like countries, states, provinces or even floodplains.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Each region has a singular value, visualized by color intensity, shading or pattern.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] The figure on the right displaying a choropleth map showing the United States' population density by state may be used as an example.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] The figure illustrates a singular value (population) denoted by blue color intensity proportionate to the state's value relative to all other states' values, bounded by each state's border.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Similarly, heat maps may also visualize data over a geographic region.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] However, unlike choropleth maps, heat maps show the proportion of a variable over an arbitrary, but usually small grid size, independent of geographic boundaries.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] The figure on the right displaying a heat map of world population is an example.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] The figure illustrates a single value (population) bounded in an arbitrary grid (square kilometers) with each cell in the grid represented by a color intensity proportionate to the value of the cell relative to all other cells.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Some heat maps that are created using approximated regional data may show familiar geographic borders in the visualization where none really exist.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] The illusion of geographic borders is due to the existence of patterns within the dataset rather than the visualization technique.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] The figure on the right displaying a heat map of world population also contains this occurrence.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Areas in rural parts of the United States and South America may closely resemble familiar geographic borders in those regions.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] Another example of a heatmap over a geographic area is a visualization of lake effect snow around Buffalo, New York, in mid-October 2006.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/heat-map] This figure shows another usage of heat maps with geographic areas, and how useful they can be in showcasing the effects of weather on specific areas as opposed to countries or states.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] In computer science, a **lookup table** (**LUT**) is an array that replaces runtime computation of a mathematical function with a simpler array indexing operation, in a process termed as ***direct addressing***.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] The savings in processing time can be significant, because retrieving a value from memory is often faster than carrying out an "expensive" computation or input/output operation.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] The tables may be precalculated and stored in static program storage, calculated (or "pre-fetched") as part of a program's initialization phase (*memoization*), or even stored in hardware in application-specific platforms.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] Lookup tables are also used extensively to validate input values by matching against a list of valid (or invalid) items in an array and, in some programming languages, may include pointer functions (or offsets to labels) to process the matching input.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] FPGAs also make extensive use of reconfigurable, hardware-implemented, lookup tables to provide programmable hardware functionality.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] LUTs differ from hash tables in that, to retrieve a value v with key k , a hash table would store the value v in the slot $h(k)$ where h is a hash function i.e. k is used to compute the slot, while in the case of LUT, the value v is stored in slot k , thus directly addressable.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] Before the advent of computers, lookup tables of values were used to speed up hand calculations of complex functions, such as in trigonometry, logarithms, and statistical density functions.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] In ancient (499 AD) India, Aryabhata created one of the first sine tables, which he encoded in a Sanskrit-letter-based number system.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] Early in the history of computers, input/output operations were particularly slow – even in comparison to processor speeds of the time.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] It made sense to reduce expensive read operations by a form of manual caching by creating either static lookup tables (embedded in the program) or dynamic prefetched arrays to contain only the most commonly occurring data items.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] Despite the introduction of systemwide caching that now automates this process, application level lookup tables can still improve performance for data items that rarely, if ever, change.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] Lookup tables were one of the earliest functionalities implemented in computer spreadsheets, with the initial version of VisiCalc (1979) including a `LOOKUP` function among its original 20 functions.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] Microsoft Excel includes multiple specialized lookup functions, with `VLOOKUP` for vertical lookup (as in a traditional lookup book), `HLOOKUP` for horizontal lookup, and (since 2019) `XLOOKUP` for outputting multiple output columns at once.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] Although the performance of an LUT is a guaranteed $O(1)$ for a lookup operation, no two entities or values can have the same key k .
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] When the size of universe U —where the keys are drawn—is large, it might be impractical or impossible to be stored in memory.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] For a trivial hash function lookup, the unsigned raw data value is used *directly* as an index to a one-dimensional table to extract a result.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] For small ranges, this can be amongst the fastest lookup, even exceeding binary search speed with zero branches and executing in constant time.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] One discrete problem that is expensive to solve on many computers is that of counting the number of bits that are set to 1 in a (binary) number, sometimes called the *population function*.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] For example, the decimal number "37" is "00100101" in binary, so it contains three bits that are set to binary "1".
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] The above implementation requires 32 operations for an evaluation of a 32-bit value, which can potentially take several clock cycles due to branching.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] It can be "unrolled" into a lookup table which in turn uses trivial hash function for better performance.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] The bits array, *bits_set* with 256 entries is constructed by giving the number of one bits set in each possible byte value (e.g.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] Sum of ones in each byte of the integer can be calculated through trivial hash function lookup on each byte; thus, effectively avoiding branches resulting in considerable improvement in performance.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] In data analysis applications, such as image processing, a lookup table (LUT) can be used to transform the input data into a more desirable output format.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] For example, a grayscale picture of the planet Saturn could be transformed into a color image to emphasize the differences in its rings.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] In image processing, lookup tables are often called **LUT**s (or 3DLUT), and give an output value for each of a range of index values.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] One common LUT, called the *colormap* or *palette*, is used to determine the colors and intensity values with which a particular image will be displayed.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] In computed tomography, "windowing" refers to a related concept for determining how to display the intensity of measured radiation.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] A classic example of reducing run-time computations using lookup tables is to obtain the result of a trigonometry calculation, such as the sine of a value.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] Calculating trigonometric functions can substantially slow a computing application.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] The same application can finish much sooner when it first precalculates the sine of a number of values, for example for each whole number of degrees (The table can be defined as static variables at compile time, reducing repeated run time costs).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] When the program requires the sine of a value, it can use the lookup table to retrieve the closest sine value from a memory address, and may also interpolate to the sine of the desired value, instead of calculating by mathematical formula.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] Lookup tables can thus be used by mathematics coprocessors in computer systems.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] An error in a lookup table was responsible for Intel's infamous floating-point divide bug.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] Functions of a single variable (such as sine and cosine) may be implemented by a simple array.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] Functions involving two or more variables require multidimensional array indexing techniques.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] The latter case may thus employ a two-dimensional array of **power[x][y]** to replace a function to calculate **xy** for a limited range of x and y values.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] Functions that have more than one result may be implemented with lookup tables that are arrays of structures.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] As mentioned, there are intermediate solutions that use tables in combination with a small amount of computation, often using interpolation.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] Pre-calculation combined with interpolation can produce higher accuracy for values that fall between two precomputed values.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] This technique requires slightly more time to be performed but can greatly enhance accuracy in applications that require it.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] Depending on the values being precomputed, precomputation with interpolation can also be used to shrink the lookup table size while maintaining accuracy.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] While often effective, employing a lookup table may nevertheless result in a severe penalty if the computation that the LUT replaces is relatively simple.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] Memory retrieval time and the complexity of memory requirements can increase application operation time and system complexity relative to what would be required by straight formula computation.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] The possibility of polluting the cache may also become a problem.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] Table accesses for large tables will almost certainly cause a cache miss.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] This phenomenon is increasingly becoming an issue as processors outpace memory.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] A similar issue appears in rematerialization, a compiler optimization.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] In some environments, such as the Java programming language, table lookups can be even more expensive due to mandatory bounds-checking involving an additional comparison and branch for each lookup.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] There are two fundamental limitations on when it is possible to construct a lookup table for a required operation.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] One is the amount of memory that is available: one cannot construct a lookup table larger than the space available for the table, although it is possible to construct disk-based lookup tables at the expense of lookup time.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] The other is the time required to compute the table values in the first instance; although this usually needs to be done only once, if it takes a prohibitively long time, it may make the use of a lookup table an inappropriate solution.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] As previously stated however, tables can be statically defined in many cases.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] Most computers only perform basic arithmetic operations and cannot directly calculate the sine of a given value.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] However, this can be expensive to compute, especially on slow processors, and there are many applications, particularly in traditional computer graphics, that need to compute many thousands of sine values every second.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] A common solution is to initially compute the sine of many evenly distributed values, and then to find the sine of *x* we choose the sine of the value closest to *x* through array indexing operation.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] This will be close to the correct value because sine is a continuous function with a bounded rate of change.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] Unfortunately, the table requires quite a bit of space: if IEEE double-precision floating-point numbers are used, over 16,000 bytes would be required.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] We can use fewer samples, but then our precision will significantly worsen.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] One good solution is linear interpolation, which draws a line between the two points in the table on either side of the value and locates the answer on that line.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] This is still quick to compute, and much more accurate for smooth functions such as the sine function.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] Linear interpolation provides for an interpolated function that is continuous, but will not, in general, have continuous derivatives.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] For smoother interpolation of table lookup that is continuous **and** has continuous first derivative, one should use the cubic Hermite spline.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] When using interpolation, the size of the lookup table can be reduced by using *nonuniform sampling*, which means that where the function is close to straight, we use few sample points, while where it changes value quickly we use more sample points to keep the approximation close to the real curve.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] For more information, see interpolation.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] Storage caches (including disk caches for files, or processor caches for either code or data) work also like a lookup table.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] A single (fast) lookup is performed to read the tag in the lookup table at the index specified by the lowest bits of the desired external storage address, and to determine if the memory address is hit by the cache.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] When a hit is found, no access to external memory is needed (except for write operations, where the cached value may need to be updated asynchronously to the slower memory after some time, or if the position in the cache must be replaced to cache another address).
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] In digital logic, a lookup table can be implemented with a multiplexer whose select lines are driven by the address signal and whose inputs are the values of the elements contained in the array.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] These values can either be hard-wired, as in an ASIC whose purpose is specific to a function, or provided by D latches which allow for configurable values.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] An *n*-bit LUT can encode any *n*-input Boolean function by storing the truth table of the function in the LUT.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] This is an efficient way of encoding Boolean logic functions, and LUTs with 4-6 bits of input are in fact the key component of modern field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs) which provide reconfigurable hardware logic capabilities.
[src:adjacency-matrix-viz/lookup-table] In some systems, polynomials may also be defined in place of lookup tables for these calculations.
